        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Those three events are relevant because
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ_msjT8iixYzGZew1SpXnIVHMAxvv2gLiZp2jRNe3q-EQrOMZ12i7mQK_Xl3NAGPPKCpWAie8bUe2dZyzuhpCHOSsc61RGf-ykhruAXW9KOZNuHxY9QfAz3BqVckbedRKcmUAqFkdRxxbSUbhyg64ALPplHF3bnMYxo8RfTGQOSxb5L2fJLfL34d43jOBr82X0zxrW2xFtOOaOaG8ZVK2jDmta1LZ0UUuMMANOotdI4UAUT0xOML0nXmTd5H3KB8XNdIsmGWIaYfJjr-POGFZd7UO30ta578OXsMcCwoHuclgfY7b2fMWCqIF0P5cKk6zOSGiH546yiEEZc7Dipyi7WrfAv-gdNMoE-" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Equi
         </a>
         is a bit of the combination of the three, with a little extra sauce on top.
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Like Robinhood, Equi is
           <strong>
            making it easier to access the financial markets
           </strong>
           .
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Like Titan, Equi is
           <strong>
            essentially a hedge fund in the back with a tech interface in the front
           </strong>
           .
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Like that poor capital allocator everyone dunked on, a large part of Equi\xe2\x80\x99s strategy is
           <strong>
            identifying and investing with the world\xe2\x80\x99s best fund managers
           </strong>
           .
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ_msjT8iixYzGZew1SpXnIVHMAxvv2gLiZp2jRNe3q-EQrOMZ12i7mQK_Xl3NAGPPKCpWAie8bUe2dZyzuhpCHOSsc61RGf-ykhruAXW9KOZNuHxY9QfAz3BqVckbedRKcmUAqFkdRxxbSUbhyg64ALPplHF3bnMYxo8RfTGQOSxb5L2fJLfL34d43jOBr82X0zxrW2xFtOOaOaG8ZVK2jDmta1LZ0UUuMMANOotdI4UAUT0xOML0nXmTd5H3KB8XNdIsmGWIaYfJjr-POGFZd7UO30ta578OXsMcCwoHuclgfY7b2fMWCqIF0P5cKk6zOSGiH546yiEEZc7Dipyi7WrfAv-gdNMoE-" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Equi
         </a>
         takes pieces from all three, and combines them into something better:
         <strong>
          a tech-powered family office in your pocket
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          (
          <strong>
           Note
          </strong>
          : when I use the term Equi throughout the piece, I\xe2\x80\x99m referring to both Equi\xe2\x80\x99s investment advisor and Equi\xe2\x80\x99s tech platform, which are two separate entities with different functions, but y\xe2\x80\x99all don\xe2\x80\x99t want to read the version that calls them different things throughout, so just know it.)
         </em>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Here\xe2\x80\x99s the thing. The way that institutional investors and Ultra-High Net Worth individuals (UHNW or the .000001%) invest is very different from the way you or I invest, even if \xe2\x80\x9cyou\xe2\x80\x9d are a High Net Worth (HNW or the 1%) individual. And it\xe2\x80\x99s certainly not because the institutions don\xe2\x80\x99t have the ability to invest the way that retail investors do\xe2\x80\xa6 they have a broader universe of options available to them than we do,
         <em>
          and
         </em>
         they mix and match those options into portfolios with better risk-adjusted returns.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The biggest difference between how they invest and how we invest?
         <strong>
          Alternative investments
         </strong>
         . Institutions and UHNW individuals, who often invest out of their own family offices, have on
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxNkcGOrCAQRb-mWRpAkXbBYjbvNwhCqaQRHCim498_bBczCSkqVVTu4ZY1CGvKpzpSQXIFjecBKsK7BECETGqBrL1TbOTPXgwTcWpw7CmexBe9ZIDd-KAwVyBHnYO3Bn2KnwlKuSCb4gakewITtncjnSc3CCoWO3MJlBmx3LqmOg_RgoIfyGeKQILaEI_y6L8e_F877_e721NeTSxoYoCzs2lvdX-FP9pXKRa_blhaajJ6G-Bvqu_HmI7sf5oD8F09nj7iBrWYkOLaPr6HlF66lu5wC_GKU86o5BPjYuxpx7rRjSNdBNDJTcYwCVIKCTMVZmFyMfYx0H3lXalzo7Wvi5VkFRPOKfu4tvZrMzuET6MB6XbvNTYQDdHMAdxtKt67-disV4iQG7HTBq-NyAYz0Kkf-G1ic72f-mtNnDRll9pU_BX9D39urBQ" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          average
         </a>
         roughly
         <strong>
          50% of their portfolios in alternative investments
         </strong>
         like hedge funds, private credit, volatility, private real estate, crypto-backed lending, and more. Even
         <strong>
          HNW investors have closer to 6%
         </strong>
         on average in alternatives.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         That creates an enormous disparity in returns over the long-term.
         <strong>
          The
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxNUk1vnDAU_DVwW4SN-TpwYL-Stsq2TaVt9oSM_QzOgqG2CeHf1yyHVrLG0sx7GsszjFpoBr0U42Csv0JllxEKBbPpwFrQ_mRAV5IXKMFZFJPc5wXhKIszX5pKaICeyq6wegJ_nOpOMmrloB4bYYhjvy1YwgXGJI1qQCiiRKRUxBhEkoicgECbL524BMWggA_Qy6DA74rW2tF4Uenhszu0D97HftANVQEbesdMxgGoVTMG7K6nijbQg7IrxT8cSmVk09p1sKf67ob-Y5pJctjZYWdb2G3ySnvRmUV0lNx60XEkYZYlMU5JnHk4aVgnuaMP7_O3QynL8fKr3Ldld5JzeZle89sz-l51lz-fX16P2dP-6XIb3-b4Ot_g5T7fTvtzh8CSa7rsyuf6628xX1_els_h8IOVP8uPY7WfT5uL0czZ0DngxpcFDjEKU5wjHCdRGKAg4UkSihjCnOeUohTSNE6hDmMqUCoo80jYNzgwU20sZff1w3xdqMHWg5aqcfK9pT10D8EFV7m7n5S0SwWK1h3wLVO7VeORctWAAu0qwytq10Kk7jEkzCOCtwxd6FEerS3BvnPmg9tS_0z_AmxXz4k" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           average HNW investor
          </a>
          has generated annualized returns of 2.5-5.4% over the past 20 years. The
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM9uhCAQxp9mudUAisiBQy9Nmr31BQjCqEREA2PNvn3Z3UOTyfzNl2_ycxZh3vNDH3tB8kwGHwfoBFeJgAiZnAWyCV6zng-t6BTxuvNsEAMJxUwZYLMhaswnkOMcY3AWw55eCkq5IIvuJYxOCVVnNzgnWkVlz2nbDYzVpn_72tMHSA40_EJ-7AlI1AviUW7t541_1biuq1nX3Lh9q1MJCKVWD5M9I9ZuCvG1ud9_zHcqYV6wmI5-MEkFo83hJxI0p5xRyRXjom9pw5re9z2dBFDllbVMgpSiPkyFnZicrLt1dJt5U86xoHXr051knXYc9xzSXM_rYjeIr0MlYGrdzhTwYSDZMYJ_w8E34xcuM0OCXNl7Y_FJVtZnOqrajr9hVHqtap-4OanOfq-q9G_6B5YfkO0" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           average UHNW investor
          </a>
          has averaged 8.8-12.4% returns over the same period.
         </strong>
         That\xe2\x80\x99s because diversifying with alternatives can increase returns and decrease volatility in a portfolio, which makes a big impact on how a portfolio grows. Throw compounding into the mix and the difference is enormous.
         <strong>
          After 20 years, $100k invested becomes $217k for the HNW investor, and $750k for the UHNW investor!
         </strong>
         The gap widens practically on its own.
        </p>
